@jima3252 Good call. In fact, now that you mention it, I think I recall their teaching this in my Power Engineering course.

I think it can get more complicated, since windings also have impedance (like an inductor), and various other factors also including typical loads rarely being purely resistive. And I think it's difficult to measure internal resistance of other types of power sources (solar, thermocouples, piezo?).

BUT as a general rule of thumb, useful-enough to be taught in EE classes, so surely would give useful results from these sorts of experiments, I think you're spot-on.

@ThinkingandTinkering Wrong.    "Electrical energy" flows through circuits.   Pure energy is just a concept and cannot "flow," but light sure does, and radio does, and low-frequency EM does.  The flow of each one is commonly expressed in watts.  Same with sound.   Same with mechanical energy traveling along a drive-shaft.   Electrical energy is stuff-like, a conserved quantity, and so it's able to flow from place to place.   
But we have no good word for "60Hz radio waves which travel along lamp-cords."   Like light and sound, it's "stuff-like," and can move along from place to place.  "Electrical energy" moves at lightspeed across bare wires, slower with plastic-covered ones  ...because it's the same stuff as light and radio.

Or, should we say that light cannot move, because light is energy, and energy cannot flow?     The same applies to radio, and to circuitry.
